Title:  Ricardos and Marxs Conception of Absolute and Relative Value: A Critical Overview 
Abstract:  This paper examines Ricardos and Marxs views on absolute and relative value, focusing on the parallels and differences in their analysis of labor values. Next, it discusses Marxâ€™s ingenious but incomplete â€œsolutionâ€\x{9D} to the problem of how it is possible for a rigorous and consistent labor theory of value to operate in a competitive capitalist economy. It then gives an overview of Sraffaâ€™s seminal contribution to the problem of constructing an invariable standard of value which meets Ricardoâ€™s exacting criteria, as well as resolving Marxâ€™s transformation conundrumâ€”one which involves abandoning the labor theory of value. The latter comes at the heavy price of discarding those qualitative and dialectal (dynamic) elements in Marxâ€™s class-based and historical approach which, more so than the classical (surplus) approach, make it such a valuable tool for understanding the social (power) relations of capitalism, as well as cutting through its ideological obfuscations. 
